<h2>Project Guidelines</h2>
<ol>
  <li>
    Please make sure that your project designs are responsive, meaning they should look and work well on all screen sizes, including desktops, tablets, and mobile devices.
  </li>
  <li>
    Use flexible layouts, media queries, and scalable images to ensure a good user experience across devices.
  </li>
  <li>
    Validate on the front-end for users, and on the back-end for security.
  </li>
  <li>
    Maintain a consistent design with colors, fonts, and spacing across all pages.
  </li>
  <li>
    Ensure accessibility by using proper headings, alt text for images, and readable contrast.
  </li>
  <li>
    Make navigation intuitive with clear menus and links.
  </li>
  <li>
    Optimize performance by compressing images and minimizing load times.
  </li>
  <li>
    Test your project on multiple devices or browser emulators to ensure responsiveness.
  </li>
  <li>
    Provide clear error handling messages for invalid inputs or system errors.
  </li>
  <li>
    Follow basic security practices by using strong parameters in Rails to permit only allowed attributes, sanitize inputs, and avoid exposing sensitive data.
  </li>
  <li>
    Do not use scaffolds in Rails; build your controllers, views, and models manually to better understand the framework.
  </li>
</ol>
